Sub-Saharan African Stocks Report: Athi, New Mauritius Hotels

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-08-24T12:59:28Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-24/sub-saharan-african-stocks-report-athi-new-mauritius-hotels.html
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index advanced
for a second day, rising 0.4 percent to 1,940.53 by the 1:30
p.m. close in  Port Louis .  Kenya ’s All-Share Index fell to its lowest in a week,
declining 0.8 percent to 62.17 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi,
the capital. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index dropped
for a fourth day, easing 0.1 percent to 22,298.59 by 1:21 p.m.
in Lagos. Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  rose 0.4 percent
to 753.35 by 1:22 p.m. in Windhoek. The Ghana Stock Exchange
Composite Index retreated for a third day, falling 1 percent to
1,165.06 by 12:23 p.m. in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Athi River Mining Ltd. (ARML)  , Kenya’s second-biggest
cement maker by market value, fell 3 shillings, or 1.8 percent,
to 165 shillings. The company has acquired limestone minefields
in  South Africa  and plans to start construction on a cement
factory in that country in two years, Business Daily reported
yesterday, citing managing director Pradeep Paunrana.  KenolKobil Ltd. (KNOC KN) the Kenyan fuel retailer with
operations in nine African countries, gained for the first day
in five, advancing 10 cents, or 1 percent, to 10.4 shillings.
Oil rose to trade near its highest closing price in four days in
 New York  after orders for U.S. durable goods climbed more than
forecast in July, restoring confidence that economic growth will
support fuel consumption.  New Mauritius Hotels Ltd. (NMH)  , the nation’s largest
leisure operator by market value, rose for a second day, gaining
0.5 rupee, or 0.6 percent, to 84.5 rupees. ENL Investment Ltd.,
a Mauritian  investment company , will buy 1.2 million shares in
the hotel group, increasing its stake. ENL will also buy 1.4
million shares and 25,000 preference shares in Tropical Paradise
Ltd. (TPL MP), a Mauritian leisure operator.  Tropical shares fell 0.25 rupees, or 3.7 percent, to 6.5
rupees.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
 sgunnion@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
